A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage was performed when the respondent was suffering from a mental disorder (Section 12(1)(a) HMA);
2. if the respondent was suffering from a mental illness or disorder at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA);
3. if the respondent was impotent at the time of the marriage and continues to be so (Section 12(1)(a) HMA, however, this is more accurately covered under Section 12(1)(a) as it pertains to the respondent's inability to consummate the marriage due to impotency);
4. if the respondent had an unsound mind or was suffering from a mental disorder at the time of registration of marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA);
5. if the marriage was performed without the respondent's consent or with their consent obtained by force, coercion, or fraud (Section 12(1)(c) HMA);
6. if the respondent was pregnant by some other person at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(d) HMA);
7. if the marriage was performed in contravention of the conditions specified in Clause (ii), (iii), (iv), (v), or (vi) of Section 5 of the HMA (Section 12(1)(e) and (f) HMA, however, these grounds pertain more to void marriages under Section 11 HMA).

